{{Infobox religious building|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | name = Tsukudo Shrine | image = [[File:Tsukudo Jinja Shrine (02) IMG 4913-4 20180519.jpg|250px|thumb|Haiden of Tsukudo Shrine]] | coordinates = {{WikidataCoord|display=inline,title}} | location = 1-14-21 Kudan-kita, Chiyoda-ku, Tokyo, Japan | deity = * {{ill|Ninigi|ja|天津彦火邇々杵尊|12=draft|12=draft}} (Amatsu Hikohono Ninigi no Mikoto) * {{ill|Taira no Masakado|ja|Taira no Masakado|1=Taira no Masakado|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|12=draft|12=draft}} | established = 940 CE | festivals = {{ill|September 15|ja|9月15日|12=draft|12=draft}} }}
'''Tsukudo Shrine''' ({{nihongo|築土神社|つくどじんじゃ}}) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in {{ill|Kudan|ja|九段|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Chiyoda|ja|千代田区|12=draft|12=draft}}, Tokyo, Japan. Also referred to as '''Tsukudo Myōjin''', it is closely associated with {{ill|Taira no Masakado}}, a legendary figure known for his rebellion and subsequent deification.
The shrine is renowned for its ''Kachimamori'' (Victory Talismans), which are popular among worshippers during New Year's celebrations.
== Enshrined Deities == Tsukudo Shrine enshrines the following deities: * {{ill|Ninigi|ja|天津彦火邇々杵尊|12=draft}} (Amatsu Hikohono Ninigi no Mikoto) – the main deity. * {{ill|Taira no Masakado|ja|Taira no Masakado|1=Taira no Masakado|12=draft|12=draft}} – a revered samurai and deified figure. * {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|12=draft|12=draft}} – the god of learning and scholarship.
During the Edo period, it was believed that the shrine housed relics such as Masakado's skull, portrait, and seated wooden figure. These were lost in the fires of the Tokyo air raids during [[World War II]], leaving only historical photographs and records.
== History == The origins of Tsukudo Shrine trace back to {{nihongo|940 CE|天慶3rd year }}, when it was established in Tsukudo Village (present-day Otemachi) to enshrine the spirit of Taira no Masakado. Over the centuries, the shrine has been relocated multiple times: * '''1580''': Moved to Kudan Hill (current Kudanzaka area) by {{ill|Ōta Dōkan|ja|太田道灌|12=draft|12=draft}}. * '''1616''': Relocated to Tsukudo Hachiman Shrine in modern-day Shinjuku due to the expansion of [[Edo Castle]]. * '''1874''': Renamed "Tsukudo Shrine" and enshrined Ninigi as the primary deity. * '''1945''': Destroyed during the Tokyo air raids and later rebuilt in 1954 at its current location. * '''1994''': Modernization of the shrine with a reinforced concrete structure.
== festivals == The shrine's primary festival is the {{nihongo|Tsukudo festival|築土祭}}, which culminates in a grand ceremony on September 15. Celebrations often include traditional mikoshi processions, with notable events such as the mikoshi entering [[Edo Castle]] in 2006 for the first time in 147 years.
== Cultural Significance == Tsukudo Shrine is recognized for its historical and cultural contributions: - The shrine's ''komainu'' (guardian lion-dog statues) and ''chikaraishi'' (power stones) are registered cultural properties of Chiyoda Ward.
== Access == The shrine is conveniently located near: * '''Kudanshita Station''' on the Tokyo Metro and Toei Subway lines.
== Gallery == <gallery> Tsukudo Jinja Shrine (01) IMG 4901-1 20180519.jpg|Pathway to the shrine Tsukudo Jinja Shrine (03) IMG 4910-3 20180519.jpg|Lion-dog statue (dated to 1780) Tsukudo Jinja Shrine (04) IMG 4907-2 20180519.jpg|Adjacent Yotsugi Inari Shrine Tsukudo Jinja Shrine (05) IMG 4915-5 20180519.jpg|View from Kudanzaka towards the main hall </gallery>
== References == {{Reflist}}
== External Links == * [http://www.tsukudo.jp/ Official Website] * [http://www.tokyo-jinjacho.or.jp/chiyoda/5542/ Tokyo Shrine Association page]
